    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-15T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-15T11:00:00-05:00" n="1262"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1262">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Stettinius Mission/29: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-15T18:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 15, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 15—3:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3088. Deles<note n="64" xml:id="d1262fn1">Designation for a series of telegrams
                        from the Under Secretary of State to the Department in connection with his
                        mission to London in April 1944. For the Under Secretary’s report to the
                        Secretary of State on his conversations in London, April 7 to April 29,
                        1944, see <ref target="frus1944v03#pg_1">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>,
                            pp. 1</ref> ff.</note> No. 13. In touching briefly on the Yugoslav
                    problem and in reply to our question Sir Orme Sargent<note n="65"
                        xml:id="d1262fn2">Sir Orme G. Sargent, Deputy Under Secretary of State in
                        the British Foreign Office.</note> remarked that somewhat to British
                    surprise King Peter’s marriage<note n="66" xml:id="d1262fn3">King Peter was
                        married to Princess Alexandra of Greece in London on March 20, 1944.</note>
                    had been subject to considerable disapproval in Yugoslavia and particularly in
                    old Serbia. He feels that it is too early to estimate how seriously this has
                    affected the King’s standing among the bulk of the Serbian population but that
                    the marriage has certainly not increased his prestige or popularity.</p>
                <pb facs="1368" n="1358" xml:id="pg_1358"/>
                <p>Both Mr. Eden and Sargent have admitted in conversation that there is no doubt of
                    Mihailovich’s great popularity in Serbia. Their information confirms the
                    Department’s feeling that he is regarded almost as a Messiah in that area.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
